definition.value: An azabicycloalkane that consists of ecgonine having benzoyl and 5-carboxypentyl groups attached to the hydroxy and carboxy functions respectively.
The 1,5-dihydro derivative of coenzyme F420-6. Species of coenzyme F420(red.) specific to Mycobacterium tuberculosis.
A coenzyme variant specific to Mycobacterium tuberculosis.
The inorganic nitrate salt of lithium.
The potassium salt of formic acid.
The inorganic dichloride salt of barium.

An ammonium betaine derivative of 3-(piperidin-1-yl)propane-1-sulfonic acid. One of a group of non-detergent sulfobetaines having a sulfobetaine hydrophilic group and a short hydrophobic group that cannot aggregate to form micelles.
The alditol 1-phosphate that is the 1-O-phospho derivative of erythritol with D configuration.
An L-glutamyl amino acid that is (2S,4S)-hypoglycin A in which the amino group has been acylated by the gamma-carboxy group of L-glutamic acid.
An alkaline earth salt that has barium(2+) as the cation.
The ketoaldose phosphate that is the 4-phosphate of 3-dehydro-L-erythrose.
The ketoaldonic acid phosphate formed formally from L-erythronic acid by oxidation of the 3-hydroxy group to an oxo group and phosphorylation at the 1-hydroxy group.
A monocarboxylic acid anion obtained by removal of a proton from the carboxylic acid group of 9(R)-HPODE.
The hydroperoxy fatty acid anion that is the conjugate base of hydroperoxy fatty acid anion, formed by deprotonation of the carboxy group; principal microspecies at pH 7.3.
A hydroxyisoflavanones that is isoflavanone bearing hydroxy groups at the 2, 7 and 4' positions, with R and S configurations at C-2 and C-3 respectively.
The parent member of the class of 3'-methoxyflavones that is flavone which carries a methoxy group at the 3'-position.
Any hydroxyisoflavone which has a hydroxy group at the 4-position of the phenyl substituent.
The parent member of the class of 4'-methoxyflavanones that is flavanone which is substituted by a methoxy group at the 4'-position.
Any substance that inhibits the action of sodium-dependent Pi-transporters.
An HPODE (hydroperoxy-octadecadienoic acid) in which the double bonds are at positions 10 and 12 (E and Z geometry, respectively) and the hydroperoxy group is at position 9 (R configuration).
An EC 3.1.3.* (phosphoric monoester hydrolase) inhibitor that interferes with the action of alkaline phosphatase (EC 3.1.3.1).
The acetate salt of L-arginyl-L-glutamic acid.
A derivative of tetracycline in which the amide function is substituted with a pyrrolidinomethyl group.
A paratose that has D-configuration.
A dideoxyhexose that is allose in which the hydroxy groups at positions 3 and 6 have been replaced by hydrogens.
The open-chain form of paratose.
A carbohydrate derivative formally obtained from a deoxy sugar.
A deoxy sugar derivative that is a derivative of a deoxy oligosaccharide.
A deoxy sugar derivative that is formally obtained from a deoxyhexose.
A deoxyhexose derivative that is formally obtained from a deoxyallose.
A deoxyhexose derivative that is formally obtained from deoxygalactose.
A deoxyhexose derivative that is formally obtained from deoxyglucose.
A deoxyhexose derivative that is formally obtained from deoxygulose.
A deoxyhexose derivative that is formally obtained from deoxymannose.
A deoxyhexose derivative that is formally obtained from a dideoxyhexose.
A deoxyhexose derivative that is formally obtained from a tetradeoxyhexose.
A deoxyhexose derivative that is formally obtained from a trideoxyhexose.
A deoxy sugar derivative that is formally obtained from a deoxyketohexose.
A deoxypentose sugar derivative that is formally obtained from a deoxyketopentose.
A deoxy sugar derivative that is formally obtained from a deoxyaldopentose.
A carbohydrate derivative that is formally obtained from a disaccharide.
An aldose derivative that is formally obtained from an aldohexose.
A deoxy sugar derivative that is formally obtained from a deoxypentose.
A disaccharide derivative that is formally obtained from a glycosyl glycoside.
A dipeptide comprising L-arginine with a L-glutamic acid residue attached to the N(1) nitrogen.
A disaccharide derivative that is formally obtained from a glycosylfructose.
